attr.attrdef: Next available ID GATEXXXX, created in IAMS
Most gates in the urban area have the parent of UOS or SPGR, with a few gates around some shopping centres in PUBP. Gate parents in the rural areas are RES, MRES, LBA and FORE.

AGRICULTURAL GATE - Farm or stock gate CATTLE GRID - cattle grid CATTLE GRID (BIKE) - cattle grid with bike access CAVELLETTI - Horse and pedestrian access only. May be wood (treated pine logs) or metal frame with treated pine logs.. CHAIN GATE - A looped chain. ENCLOSURE PEDESTRIAN - Big pedestrian gate mesh 2m high topped with barbed wire TNR, wildlife, depots, Mulligans Flat predator proof. ENCLOSURE VEHICLE - Vehicle big gate mesh 2m high topped with barbed wire TNR, wildlife, depots, Mulligans Flat predator proof. LOG GATE - A log barrier that can be removed. They are heavy and are being replaced PEDESTRIAN GATE - A small gap or gate in a stock fence, not wide enough for vehicles, includes horse gates eg Pine Is. PIPE GATE - Boom gates made of pipe. REMOVABLE BOLLARD METAL - removable bollard metal REMOVABLE BOLLARD WOOD - removable bollard wood SECURITY - Vehicle big gate mesh 2m high topped with barbed wire TNR, wildlife, depots, Mulligans Flat predator proof. Same as “Enclosed Vehicle”. SQUEEZE POST - A small gap in the fence, not wide enough for vehicles. STEP GATE - Style SUPERGATE - A heavy duty pipe gate. May be single or double width. Designed to withstand high vandalism. TYPE NOT KNOWN
Managers include: null, CS, NAC, PAC, PCS, Private, Roads_ACT, SAR, SPGR, Unknown

dataIdInfo.idAbs: Location of gates that are publicly managed by the ACT Government and located with Urban Open Space, Reserve, Land Managed as Reserve, Horse Paddocks or Land Bank. Attributes include: gate ID, IAMS ID (GATE), division name, location description, parent reference, gate type (eg agricultural, cattle grid, pipe gate etc), Manager, sign (yes, no), number of gates (single, double), feature type codeand dataset entry creation date. Privately managed gates and flood danger/road closure gates within Reserves that are managed by RoadsACT, are not shown. These assets are managed by Parks and Territory Services (PATS), within TAMS. The PATS branch is therefore the source of asset data. The data is then managed in the Integrated Asset Management System (IAMS) on behalf of PATS by the Asset Information and Management Services Branch. Gate locations are stored as individual points.

Consts.useLimit: Direct access to data within the ACT Integrated Asset Management System (IAMS) is limited to internal users. The custodian is responsible for the maintenance and distribution of the data. The distribution of data to external users can usually be done in any format compatible with Oracle OSD software or capable of being converted using FME software, subject to custodian approval.

ConResult.conExpl: Although this dataset is updated on a regular basis it will always have a backlog of entries hence it is not a true reflection of the all the government owned assets depicted in this dataset. Similar assets within the Australian Capital Territory that are owned and/or managed privately or by other agencies or state government are also excluded. Some locations are indicative depending on the underlying systems that they are managed by or how the data was captured. Data may also be omitted from the dataset if it refers to an asset that is not currently operational.

dataLineage.statement: The dataset titled CGDMGA.GATE is maintained in the Integrated Asset Management System (IAMS) by the Asset Information and Management Services Branch within Territory and Municipal Services (TAMS) on behalf of Parks and Territory Services (PATS). The information is sourced from audits undertaken by asset maintenance staff within PATS and from Works As Executed drawings provided by contractors. The raw data is then processed by officers within Asset Information and Management Services to conform to the Oracle database (Oracle SDO version 11.2) used for the ACT Government IAMS. The IAMS stores data in the ACT Stromlo Projection. Spatial layers within the IAMS are created from Oracle views, effectively joining the spatial table to an Asset Inventory table using system generated unique identifiers. Spatial layers are points, lines or polygons, tested for valid or invalid geometries in ESRI ArcGIS software (version 10.3.1).\ Since 1995, gate data was collected by staff, students and others uisng GPS "Garmin GPS II Plus" to collect points. Downloaded in PCX5 and converted to Arcview with GarmapXL. Points converted into lines by heads up digitising on the screen at about 1 to 4,000 metre scale. Attributes added in Arcview and Excel.
